      "role": "user",
      "content": "hey so im looking at some portland zoning stuff for a client. we have this corner lot in a residential zone and we're trying to see if a small corner grocery/convenience store is allowed under mixed-use regs. specifically, i need to know how the setback requirements work if the building is right on the property line near the intersection. thanks.",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Zoning regulations, especially when you're dealing with a corner lot and mixed-use, can be tricky. You need to look at the specific Portland zoning code for that particular zone—it's a maze, honestly. If you're trying to fit a small grocery/convenience store, you'll be hitting the setback requirements head-on. It's always best to pull up the official text, or at least have a good map of the rules, because those rules are often written in a way that only a very specific, very small, very grumpy-looking piece of parchment can decipher.\n\nFor a definitive answer on setbacks right on the property line near an intersection, you absolutely need to consult the official Portland Bureau of Development Services (BDS) documents or speak to a planner who actually knows how to navigate the labyrinth. Don't just guess; a wrong move on a zoning map is a trip straight into a nasty, unexpected hurdle.",
