    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "fair enough. i'll check the BDS site. but just generally, when we're looking at mixed-use in these residential areas, how does the city handle \"encroachments\" or when a new structure's footprint starts pushing right up against the existing zoning boundaries? do they just deny the permit or is there a process for variances?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "In the city, when a new structure starts pushing right up against the zoning boundaries—what they call an \"encroachment\"—it's usually a big deal. The city doesn't just shrug and let it slide; that's not how the system works. If you're trying to squeeze something in where the rules say \"no,\" you're looking at a potential denial, or you're going to have to go through the tedious, often slow, process of seeking a variance.\n\nA variance, you see, is like asking the zoning committee to look the other way for a little while. It’s a negotiation, and it’s usually a tough one, because the city wants order, and a structure pushing too close is just chaos in their eyes. Think of it like a small, well-armed plea to the local council.",
      "source": "target",
